{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15178"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15178"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.14,0.69,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64616"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7869"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50050"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8138"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21311"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64616"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal wall hernias can form at any site where there is a weakness in the anatomical structures. One such sit is Hesselbach\u0027s triangle. This is an important anatomical landmark in the anterior abdominal wall that has clinical significance in hernia formation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of hernia occurs through Hesselbach\u0027s triangle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epigastric","Femoral","Inguinal","Paraumbilical","Spigelian"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHesselbach\u0027s triangle is the anatomical region where direct \u003Cstrong\u003Einguinal \u003C/strong\u003Ehernias occur. It is bounded by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaterally: inferior epigastric vessels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedially: lateral border of rectus abdominis muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInferiorly: inguinal ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect hernias protrude through the posterior wall of the inguinal canal. Indirect inguinal hernias pass lateral to the inferior epigastric vessels through the deep inguinal ring. \u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral \u003C/strong\u003Ehernias occur below the inguinal ligament through the femoral canal. \u003Cstrong\u003EParaumbilical \u003C/strong\u003Ehernias occur immediately adjacent to the umbilicus. \u003Cstrong\u003EEpigastric \u003C/strong\u003Ehernias occur in the linea alba above the umbilicus. \u003Cstrong\u003ESpigelian\u003C/strong\u003E hernias occur at the junction between the linea semilunaris and the arcuate line.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hesselbach\u0027s triangle is the anatomical region where direct inguinal hernias occur.","Hesselbach\u0027s triangle is bounded by the inferior epigastric vessels, lateral border of rectus abdominis, and inguinal ligament."],"references":["Hammoud M, Gerken J. Inguinal Hernia. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513332/","Conze J, Klinge U, Schumpelick V. Hernias. In: Holzheimer RG, Mannick JA, editors. Surgical Treatment: Evidence-Based and Problem-Oriente